# This is a TEMPLATE, not a real .htpasswd. Do not upload as-is.
#
# Generate the real file with one of these methods, then upload it (no
# extension change) to the path you referenced in deploy/staging.htaccess
# under AuthUserFile.
#
# Method 1 — htpasswd CLI (recommended; available on macOS / DreamHost shell):
#   htpasswd -c -B /tmp/staging.htpasswd alex
#   (-c creates a new file; -B uses bcrypt. Enter the password when prompted.)
#
# Method 2 — DreamHost web panel:
#   Panel → Domains → Manage Websites → (staging.alexmchong.ca) → Password
#   protection. DreamHost generates and installs both files for you.
#
# Method 3 — Online generator (only if you trust the tool):
#   https://www.web2generators.com/apache-tools/htpasswd-generator
#   Choose bcrypt, paste username/password, copy the line into a file.
#
# File format (one line per user):
#   username:$2y$10$<bcrypt-hash>
#
# Example (the hash below is FAKE — do not use):
#   alex:$2y$10$abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789ABCDEFGHIJ.KLMNOP
#
# Notes:
# - Store the password in 1Password under "alexmchong.ca staging".
# - .htpasswd should be readable by the Apache user, mode 644 is fine.
# - If you can place .htpasswd OUTSIDE the webroot, do — it is one less file
#   for a misconfigured server to leak. DreamHost shared hosting usually
#   permits absolute paths above the domain webroot.
